Additional instructions for VSCode on HPC
Updated 1 week ago by Panagiotis Lymperopoulos
Prerequisites
Before you begin, ensure you have:

Your Tufts UTLN (username, e.g., jjumbo01).
Visual Studio Code installed with the Remote - SSH extension (should also work with vscode forks e.g. Cursor)
An SSH key pair generated and registered (e.g., id_ed25519), with the private key on your local machine.
Make sure to transfer that ssh key to the cluster (login-prod.pax.edu) otherwise you may have issue setting up vscode
Step 1: SSH into the Login Node
First, you need to access the cluster’s login node via your local terminal. The login node is the gateway to the cluster; you should never run heavy code directly on it.

Open your local terminal (or VS Code integrated terminal).
Run the following SSH command, replacing <your_utln> with your actual Tufts username:
ssh <your_utln>@login-prod.pax.tufts.edu

You should see the Pax Cluster welcome message featuring the elephant ASCII art.
Step 2: Request an Interactive Compute Node
Once on the login node, you must request resources from the job scheduler (SLURM) to get a dedicated compute node where you can safely run your assignments.

Run the following srun command to request a node with 1 task, 16GB of memory, and a 4-hour time limit:
srun --ntasks=1 --time=0-4:00:00 --mem 16g --pty bash

The terminal will display srun: job <job_id> queued and waiting for resources followed by srun: job <job_id> has been allocated resources.
Important: Note the name of the compute node you are assigned in your new prompt (e.g., [<your_utln>@pax046 ~]$). In this example, the node is pax046. You will need this for the next step.
Step 3: Configure VS Code for the Compute Node
Now that you have a compute node assigned, you need to tell VS Code how to connect to it.

Open VS Code and navigate to the Remote Explorer tab on the left sidebar.
In the SSH section, click the Gear icon (⚙️) to open your SSH configuration file.
Select your user config file (usually ~/.ssh/config on Mac/Linux or C:\Users\Name\.ssh\config on Windows).
Add the following template to the file. Update the <assigned_node>, <your_utln>, and your IdentityFile path to match your setup:
# Optional: Entry for the login node
Host login.pax.tufts.edu
    HostName login-prod.pax.tufts.edu
    User <your_utln>
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519 

# Entry for your specific compute node
Host <assigned_node>.pax.tufts.edu
    HostName <assigned_node>.pax.tufts.edu
    User <your_utln>
    IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
